\subsection*{Low-Distortion Implies Good Preservation}

In order to directly compare $\alpha$-preservation and $\frac{1}{\alpha}$-distortion embeddings, we broaden the definition of $\alpha$-preservation to apply to metric spaces:

\begin{definition}
   For a metric space \((\mathcal{Z},\sigma)\), let \(G_R(\mathcal{Z})   (\mathcal{Z}, E)\) denote the graph where \((z,w) \in E \iff {\sigma(z,w) < R}\). We say a map \(f:(\mathcal{Z},\sigma)\to (\X,\rho)\) is an \((\alpha,R)\)-preservation of \((\mathcal{Z},\rho)\) for \(\alpha\in (0,2)\) and \(R>0\) if its output is an \(\alpha\)-preservation of \(G_R(\mathcal{Z})\).
\end{definition}

Note that $(\alpha, 2)$-preserving $G \in \Gn$ with respect to the shortest path metric coincides precisely with the regular definition of $\alpha$-preserving $G$. Consider the classical notion of structure retaining embedding:

\begin{definition}[\citet{matousek2013lectures}]\label{def:distortion} Fix any $\alpha \leq 1$.   A mapping $f: (\mathcal{Z}, \sigma) \to (\X, \rho)$ is called a \emph{$\frac{1}{\alpha}$-distortion}, if there exist $c>0$ such that for all $u,v \in \mathcal{Z}$:
$$\alpha c \cdot \sigma(u,v) \leq \rho(f(u),f(v)) \leq c \cdot \sigma(u,v).$$
\end{definition}


It is not hard to see that $\alpha$-preservation is strictly weaker than $\frac{1}{\alpha}$-distortion.

\begin{observation}\label{obs:DistortionImpliesPreservationMetric}
   For any $\alpha \leq 1$. If $f$ constitutes an $\frac{1}{\alpha}$-distortion\footnote{Note that $(\frac{1}{\alpha} < 1)$-distortion is impossible by definition.} of $ \mathcal{Z}$, then for all $R>0$, $f$ is an $(\alpha,R)$-preservation of $\mathcal{Z}$. In particular, if $\mathcal{Z}G\in\Gn$ is equipped with the shortest path metric, then $f$ constitutes an $\alpha$-preservation of $G.$
\end{observation}


\begin{proof}
   \todo[inline]{Note that this proof is not as formal as it should be because it is so obvious it probably does not need to be included into the paper.}
   Let $f$ be a $(1/\alpha)$-distortion embedding. Then there exists $c>0$ s.t.\ for all $x,y \in \mathcal{Z}$: $c \cdot \sigma(x,y) \leq \rho(f(x),f(y)) \leq \frac{c}{\alpha} \cdot \sigma(x,y).$ Thus setting $r : cR/\alpha$:
   $$\sigma( u, v) < R \implies \rho(f_G(v), f_G(w)) < cR/\alpha   r$$
   $$\sigma( u, v) \geq R \implies \rho(f_G(v), f_G(w)) \geq cR   \alpha \cdot r. $$
\end{proof}
To see that this weakness is strict, consider $\frac{1}{\alpha}$-distortion an $n$-point unit simplex in $\mathbb{R}^n$. The doubling dimension of the embedding will be $\Omega\big(\frac{\log(n)}{\log(\alpha)}\big)$, whereas $\alpha$-preservation takes $0$ dimensions for $R > 1$ and $1$ dimension for $R \leq 1$. 
